24/03/20, 10:32 pm - Manjunath S Nayak: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

void swap(int* a, int* b)
{
    int t = *a;
    *a = *b;
    *b = t;
}
int partition (int row[], int col[], int low, int high)
{
    int pivot = row[high];   
    int i = (low - 1);  

    for (int j = low; j <= high- 1; j++)
    {
        
        if (row[j] < pivot)
        {
            i++;   
            swap(&row[i], &row[j]);
            swap(&col[i], &col[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(&row[i + 1], &row[high]);
    swap(&col[i + 1], &col[high]);
    return (i + 1);
}

void quickSort(int row[], int col[], int low, int high)
{
    if (low < high)
    {
        int pi = partition(row, col, low, high);

        quickSort(row, col, low, pi - 1);
        quickSort(row, col, pi + 1, high);
    }
}
//quick sort from geeks for geeks - slightly modified 
int main()
{
  	/*M C Sohan*/
	//here there be dragons
    int R, C, K, D;
    scanf ("%d %d %d %d", &R, &C, &K, &D);
    int row[D];
    int col[D];
    //read in the row and the column numbers of the D dragons
    for (int i =0;i<D;i++)
        scanf ("%d %d", &row[i], &col[i]);
    quickSort(row, col, 0, D-1);
    //sort the dragons according to the rows
    //initialize the 2D array to hold the required information for dynamic programming
    int mindist[D][K], min, temp;
    //this is the initialization step
    //for k = 1
    for (int i = 0;i<D;i++)
        mindist[i][0] = row[i]+col[i];
  //rows represent the kill number and columns represent the dragon number
    for (int j =1;j<K;j++)
    {
        //going column by column
        for (int i = j;i<D;i++)
        {
            min = mindist[j-1][j-1] + row[i]-row[j-1] + abs(col[i]-col[j-1]);
          	//initialize the minimum distance
            for (int k = j;k<i;k++)
            {
              	//check for minimum distance for pair (i,j) for the possible values
                temp = mindist[k][j-1] + row[i]-row[k] + abs(col[i]-col[k]);
                min = (temp<min)?temp:min;
            }
            mindist[i][j] = min;
        }
    }
    min = mindist[K-1][K-1];
  	//get the absolute minimum distance
    for (int i =K;i<D;i++)
        min = (min<mindist[i][K-1])?min:mindist[i][K-1];
    printf ("%d\n", min);//print the absolute minimum distance 
    return 0;
}

import java.util.stream.Stream;
import java.util.Scanner;
public class Pattern2 {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
	  	int n = new Scanner(System.in).nextInt();
      	for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
      		Stream.generate(()->" ").limit((n-i)).forEach(System.out::print);
        	Stream.generate(()->"* ").limit(i).forEach(System.out::print);
        	System.out.println("");
        }
    }
}
25/03/20, 7:36 pm - Manoj Rvce: Week 8: PA3

import java.util.stream.Stream;
import java.io.*;

public class Pattern3 {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    int n = Integer.parseInt(new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in)).readLine());
    int max = (2*n) - 1, spaceCount = (2*n) - 2;
    
    for(int i = 1; i <= max; i += 2, spaceCount -= 2) {
      Stream.generate(() -> " ").limit(spaceCount).forEach(System.out::print);
      for(int j = 1; j <= i; j++)
        System.out.print(j + " ");
      System.out.println("");
    }
    System.out.println((n * (n+1) * ((4*n)-1)) / 6);
  }
}
25/03/20, 7:36 pm - Manoj Rvce: Week 8 java: c a a c d a b c d a
25/03/20, 7:36 pm - Manoj Rvce: Week 8: PA4

import java.util.stream.Stream;
import java.io.*;

public class Pattern4 {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    int l = Integer.parseInt(new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in)).readLine());
    if(l % 2 == 0)
      System.out.print("Invalid line number");
    else {
      int half = l / 2;
      for(int i = 1; i <= half + 1; i++) {
        Stream.generate(() -> " ").limit(half - i + 1).forEach(System.out::print);
        Stream.generate(() -> "* ").limit(i).forEach(System.out::print);
        System.out.println("");
      }
      for(int i = half; i >= 1; i--) {
        Stream.generate(() -> " ").limit(half - i).forEach(System.out::print);
        Stream.generate(() -> " *").limit(i).forEach(System.out::print);
        System.out.println("");
      }
    }
  }
}
25/03/20, 7:36 pm - Manoj Rvce: Week 8: PA5

import java.io.*;

public class Pattern5 {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    int n = Integer.parseInt(new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in)).readLine());
    
    if(n == 1)
      System.out.println("   \n  |\n  |");
    else if(n == 2)
      System.out.println(" _ \n _|\n|_ ");
    else if(n == 3)
      System.out.println(" _ \n _|\n _|");
    else if(n == 4)
      System.out.println("   \n|_|\n  |");
    else if(n == 5)
      System.out.println(" _ \n|_ \n _|");
    else if(n == 6)
      System.out.println(" _ \n|_ \n|_|");
    else if(n == 7)
      System.out.println(" _ \n  |\n  |");
    else if(n == 8)
      System.out.println(" _ \n|_|\n|_|");
    else if(n == 9)
      System.out.println(" _ \n|_|\n _|");
    else if(n == 0)
      System.out.println(" _ \n| |\n|_|");
  }
}

01/04/20, 10:42 pm - Likith S R RV: Explanation 1 : We will solve this using MST Cycle property, which says that, "For any cycle C in the graph, if the weight of an edge e of C is larger than the weights of all other edges of C, then this edge cannot belong to an MST."
Step 1
Run dfs from one of the end-points(either u or v) of the edge E considering only those edges that have weight less than that of E.
Step 2
Case 1 If at the end of this dfs, the vertices u and v get connected, then edge E cannot be a part of some MST. This is because in this case there definitely exists a cycle in the graph with the edge E having the maximum weight and it cannot be a part of the MST(from the cycle property).
Case 2 But if at the end of the dfs u and v stay disconnected, then edge E must be the part of some MST as in this case E is always not the maximum weight edge in all the cycles that it is a part of.
01/04/20, 10:42 pm - Manjunath S Nayak: Keep submitting
01/04/20, 10:43 pm - Manjunath S Nayak: Damn bro
01/04/20, 10:43 pm - Amaan RV CS: fuckk
01/04/20, 10:43 pm - Likith S R RV: Explanation 2 : By negating the weights, observe that it is equivalent to finding the maximum-weight feedback edge set. To find a maximum-weight feedback edge set, build an MST using either Prim's or Kruskal's algorithm. Then take the complement of that MST to obtain minimum weight feedback edge set.

10/04/20, 11:06 pm - Likith S R RV: Technique applied : A* Algorithm (Combinatorial Optimization) and Priority Queues

You can use the heuristic that is based on the positions of the numbers, that is the higher the overall sum of all the distances of each letter from its goal state is, the higher the heuristic value. Then you can implement A* search which can be proved to be the optimal search in terms of time and space complexity 

We can order the moves with the help of a special queue that orders based on priority. The priority is determined by taking the current heuristic value and adding it to the depth. This gives us our A* (a star) value for a particular state. If the queue is ordered properly (lowest first), the next best move is always "next in line" for expansion. This process will always yield the correct solution in the least number of moves, as long as the puzzle is initially a solvable state.

The A* searching algorithm is a recursive algorithm that continuously calls itself until a winning state is found. When the game is designed, in order to randomly generate different games, start with the goal state and make many random moves on the state.



Algorithm PseudoCode :

 boolean
Solution::search(PriorityQueue pq)
{ if pq.isEmpty() then
	return false
puz = pq.extract()
if puz.isGoal()
	return true
successors = puz.expand()
            	// all possible successors to puz
for each suc in successors do
	pq.insert(suc)
if search(pq)
	return true
else
	return false
}

20/04/20, 12:21 pm - Manoj Rvce: The password is set as‚Äù5555‚Äù.Henc, only when the user enters this key, the door will open.

void delay(): This is a function to generate delay of certain milliseconds.For loops are used to generate this delay.
 
The rows and columns of the keypad are defined.

int main(): The PLCLK is taken to be 60MHz. The direction is set for output in ports 1 and 0(pin 16 and pins 2,3,4,5,6,7,28,29,30,31 respectively). The first line‚Äôs position(0x80) is set using the cmd function and the user is asked to enter the password in order to enter inside. The second line‚Äôs position is set and the password entered is stored in an array rx_arr[]. The password is displayed as ‚Äù*‚Äù using the dat() method.Now, the password entered by the user is verified against the actual password and accordingly messages like‚Äùthank you‚Äù(for correct password) and‚Äù wrong password‚Äùare displayed in the second line(0xc0). If the user has entered the correct password, then lpc2148 sends signals to the motor driver which inturn signals the dc motor to rotate in clockwise direction using the forward() function, which opens the door. After which a certain delay is obtained using the delay() function and the dc motor stops rotating (stop()) . Later again, the message‚Äùcome again‚Äù is displayed followed by a delay of a few milliseconds and lpc2148 sends signals to the motor driver which in turn signals the dc motor to rotate anticlockwise which closes the door and then stops rotating(stop()). If the password entered is wrong, then there is a delay of certain milliseconds and the screen is cleared(cmd(0x01)).

unsigned char keypad(): Here the row and column of the key entered by the user is decided using variables like r_loc and c_loc which store the row number and column number . Also, the variables c1,c2,c3 hold the addresses of the columns 1,2,3 respectively. Initially the column is decided using the if-else conditions. Pins 16,17,18,19 are used to decide the row.
Initially, pin 16 is cleared and the rest at set, check for the column is done, if either of the columns are cleared, r_loc=0, else next pin 17 is cleared and the rest are set, and again if either of the columns are cleared, r_loc=1, similarly 18,19 are cleared one after the other incase r_loc is still not found. Hence, after r_loc and c_loc are found, these positions are used to figure out the key from the 2D array defined at the start, and is returned.
Void lcd_init(): this method initialises the lcd i.e., sets the cursor position, sets the address of the first row etc.cmd(0x02);             //initialise lcd in 4bit mode
    cmd(0x28);                //2 lines on display
    cmd(0x0c);                //display on cursor off
    cmd(0x06);                //auto increment cursor
    cmd(0x80);                //first line position

void cmd(unsigned char a): The upper nibble of command is selected first, then pin 2 is cleared(rs=0 -> writing command byte into command register of LCD),pin 1 is cleared(rw=0 ->write command to LCD), and pin 3 is set (en=1, to perform writing/reading for 450nsec) and delay of certain milliseconds is obtained using lcd_delay() method to start with lower nibble. Also, pin 3 is cleared (en=0,perform read/write when pulse goes from high to low). Now, the lower nibble of command is selected, similar pins are set and cleared. Hence, using this method, the desired pins are set and cleared in order to write data.

void show(unsigned char *s): It gets the address of string to be displayed on lcd. Every character is extracted from the string and sent to the function dat() , in order to set and clear certain pins so that the string is displayed on lcd.

void dat(unsigned char b): It gets the character from show() method, it works similar to cmd function. But here instead of command, data is written. The upper nibble is selected and pin2 is set(rs=1, ->writing data into data register of lcd), pin1 is cleared(rw=0,->write data to lcd), pin 3 is set(en=1,->to perform read/write for 450nsec) after which delay is set using lcd_delay method. Now, the lower nibble is selected, pin2 is set(rs=1), pin 1 is cleared(rw=0), pin 3 is set(en=1). Hence, data is written on lcd.

void lcd_delay(): Here for loop is used to generate delay of certain milliseconds. Delay is essential as there should be some time gap between operations performed on upper nibble and lower nibble in order for them not to overlap which doesn‚Äôt give the desired output and also, so that the output is visible on the screen for some noticeable time.

void forward(): This method drives the  dc motor  to rotate in clockwise direction after receiving signals from the motor driver(l232d). Only when the user enters the correct password, the motor rotates in clockwise direction and the door opens. The pins 16 or 18 are set and pin 17 is cleared , to achieve this. 

Void reverse():this method drives the  dc motor  to rotate in anti- clockwise after receiving signals from the motor driver(l232d). Only when the user enters the correct password, the door opens and after that the dc motor rotates in an anti-clockwise direction to close the door. The pins 17 or 18 are set and pin 16 is cleared , to achieve this.
Void stop():here pin 18 is cleared. The method helps in stopping the rotation of the dc motor in both clockwise and anti-clockwise direction, once the door is open and closed respectively.

18/05/20, 8:08 am - Manoj Rvce: # Python3 program to construct  
# tree from given Prufer Code  
  
# Prints edges of tree represented 
# by give Prufer code  
def printTreeEdges(prufer, m): 
      
    vertices = m + 2
      
    # Initialize the array of vertices  
    vertex_set = [0] * vertices 
      
    # Number of occurrences of vertex in code  
    for i in range(vertices - 2): 
        vertex_set[prufer[i] - 1] += 1
      
    print("The edge set E(G) is :") 
      
    # Find the smallest label not present in  
    # prufer.  
    j = 0
    for i in range(vertices - 2): 
        for j in range(vertices): 
              
            # If j+1 is not present in prufer set  
            if (vertex_set[j] == 0): 
                  
                # Remove from Prufer set and print  
                # pair.  
                vertex_set[j] = -1
                print("(" , (j + 1),", ",prufer[i],") ",sep = "",end = "") 
                vertex_set[prufer[i] - 1] -= 1
                break
      
    j = 0
      
    # For the last element  
    for i in range(vertices): 
        if (vertex_set[i] == 0 and j == 0): 
            print("(", (i + 1),", ", sep="", end="") 
            j += 1
        elif (vertex_set[i] == 0 and j == 1): 
            print((i + 1),")") 
  
# Driver code  
prufer = [4, 1, 3, 4] 
n = len(prufer)  
printTreeEdges(prufer, n)  
  
# This code is contributed by SHUBHAMSINGH10
